{"id":14880786,"mediaExerciseId":"85fcfe47-f8ab-4164-ab82-bf1db4bc3ddd","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612274,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":84,"solutions":[{"id":5908255,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to explain the different current ratios provided. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/23c1aff23eee3d52094a886113654372/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/23c1aff23eee3d52094a886113654372/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define current ratio.\n\n**Current ratio** is a financial ratio which shows if a company can pay its current liabilities by maximizing its current assets.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Current ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Current Assets}} {\\text{Current Liabilities}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":231,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/c4a77cc024de468b7e2277018104e728/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":118,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/c4a77cc024de468b7e2277018104e728/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"If the current ratio is 0.50, this means that the firm has twice as much current liabilities than its current assets. The firm has poor liquidity and might have difficulty meeting its short-term obligations. \n\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/423a1372abd2569f3f19dc8b5f2a28b9/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/423a1372abd2569f3f19dc8b5f2a28b9/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"If the current ratio is 1.50, this means the firm has 50% more current assets than its current liabilities. The firm has improved in liquidity and  short-term obligations can be met.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"If the current ratio is 15.0, this means the firm has excess cash sitting in current assets with little to no return. The firm need to put the excess cash to better use by investing in long-term assets or distributing dividends to its shareholders.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":136,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/4a26f99fc97e441be019b6558cd79677/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/0c288bfb22aeb242310750568a71f19e/4a26f99fc97e441be019b6558cd79677/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"d263e414-34b4-4c13-9799-ce3f04751b6f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","i